## ✅ Lesson 4 — HTTP Methods (Deep Understanding with Real HPM Examples)

In **REST API**, the most important concept is **HTTP Methods**.

Every API call you test in your **Philips HPM Support Tool** will use one of these methods.

Without understanding HTTP methods, you cannot do API automation.

---

## 🔹 1. What are HTTP Methods

HTTP methods tell the server **what action to perform**.

| Method | Meaning                    |
| ------ | -------------------------- |
| GET    | Read data                  |
| POST   | Create / Login / Send data |
| PUT    | Update data                |
| DELETE | Delete data                |
| PATCH  | Partial update             |

In healthcare support tools, most used:

✅ GET
✅ POST
✅ PUT
✅ DELETE

---

## 🔹 2. Real Flow in HPM Support Tool

```text
UI → API → Backend → DB / Device → Response → UI
```

HTTP method decides what API will do.

Example:

| Action         | API          | Method |
| -------------- | ------------ | ------ |
| Login          | /api/login   | POST   |
| Get devices    | /api/devices | GET    |
| Connect device | /api/connect | POST   |
| Update config  | /api/config  | PUT    |
| Delete user    | /api/user    | DELETE |

QA must test all.

---

## 🔹 3. GET Method (Read Data)

GET = Fetch data from server

Example:

```http
GET /api/devices
```

Response:

```json
[
  {"id":1,"status":"connected"},
  {"id":2,"status":"disconnected"}
]
```

Used in HPM for:

* Device list
* Logs
* Features
* Role data
* Patient data

QA checks:

* Status code
* Data correct
* Role allowed
* No error

Real scenario:

FSE → can see devices
User → cannot see devices

So API must return different data.

---

## 🔹 4. POST Method (Create / Send Data)

POST = send data to server

Used for:

* Login
* Connect device
* Create config
* Send command
* Add user

Example login:

```http
POST /api/login
```

Body:

```json
{
  "username": "azeez",
  "password": "123"
}
```

Response:

```json
{
  "token": "abc123",
  "role": "FSE"
}
```

QA checks:

* Token present
* Role correct
* Status code
* Error handling

---

## 🔹 5. PUT Method (Update Data)

PUT = update existing data

Used for:

* Update settings
* Update config
* Update device info
* Update user

Example:

```http
PUT /api/config
```

Body:

```json
{
  "mode": "service"
}
```

Response:

```json
{
  "status": "updated"
}
```

QA checks:

* Update success
* DB updated
* Role allowed

---

## 🔹 6. DELETE Method (Remove Data)

DELETE = remove data

Used for:

* Delete user
* Delete config
* Remove device
* Clear logs

Example:

```http
DELETE /api/user/5
```

Response:

```json
{
  "status": "deleted"
}
```

QA checks:

* User removed
* DB updated
* Permission correct

---

## 🔹 7. Real Role-Based Scenario (Very Important)

Admin login

```http
GET /api/features
```

Response:

```json
["enumerator","config","logs","connect"]
```

Normal user login

```http
GET /api/features
```

Response:

```json
["dashboard"]
```

Same API
Different response
Because role is different.

QA must test this.

This is very common in Philips tools.

